{
  "task": "transcribe",
  "language": "english",
  "duration": 68.68000030517578,
  "text": "What you see here is a poem, it's more than 90 characters long, and every single one of them is pronounced exactly the same way, shi. In Chinese, somehow that actually works. It's called The Lion-Eating Poet in the Stone Den, written by the linguist Yuan Renchao. 90-something characters, and the only thing separating them is their tone. Now I am not going to read it aloud, but I got some help from Google Translate. Shi, shi, shi, shi. Four flavors of a single syllable, shi, shi, shi, shi, shi. To your ears, to anyone's ears, it's pure nonsense, a wall of the exact same sound. Nobody could follow it, but now look at it written down. Suddenly it's a crisp little story. A poet named Shi, who's obsessed with eating lions, vows to eat ten of them. He goes to the market, finds ten lions, kills them, hauls them home, and discovers they were actually ten stone lions. Every shi is a different character, with a different meaning. On paper, there's zero confusion. And that's the whole trick. Chinese characters carry meaning by their shape, not their sound. Want to actually start learning Chinese? Discover thousands of free exercises and more learning content on stacktags.io.",
